(44, 7, 33, 2, 3, 5, 5, 'put off thy shoes from thy feet', 'Connection of Holy Ground', 'Both passages emphasize the command to ''put off thy shoes from thy feet'' in the context of holy ground. This connection highlights the sacredness of the location where God speaks.', 'quotation', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 33, 6, 5, 15, 15, 'for the place where thou standest is holy', 'Holy Ground Command', 'Both passages emphasize the command to remove shoes in the presence of holy ground. This connection highlights the sacredness of the locations where God reveals Himself.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 33, 21, 5, 1, 1, 'holy ground', 'Holiness and Reverence', 'This connection highlights the theme of holiness in approaching God. Both passages emphasize the need for reverence, as seen in ''holy ground'' and ''keep thy foot.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 33, 61, 1, 18, 18, 'holy ground', 'Holy Ground and Holy Mount', 'This connection highlights the concept of holiness in both passages. Acts 7:33 refers to a place as ''holy ground,'' while 2 Peter 1:18 mentions a ''holy mount,'' emphasizing the sacredness of these locations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 2, 3, 7, 10, 'I have seen, I have seen', 'Divine Deliverance of Israel', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of Israel''s affliction and His intention to deliver them from Egypt. The repetition of phrases like ''I have seen'' and ''I am come down to deliver them'' underscores this connection.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 2, 4, 31, 31, NULL, 'Divine Response to Affliction', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s awareness and response to the affliction of His people. Both passages emphasize God''s observation of suffering and His intention to deliver, leading to the people''s worship in response to His intervention.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 16, 9, 9, 9, 'affliction of my people which is in Egypt', 'Affliction and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of the affliction of His people in Egypt and His response to their cries for help. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s concern and action in delivering His people from suffering.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 19, 106, 44, 44, 'affliction of my people which is in Egypt', 'Affliction and Divine Response', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of affliction and His response to the cries of His people. Acts 7:34 speaks of God seeing the affliction and hearing the groaning, while Psalms 106:44 highlights His regard for their affliction when He hears their cry.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 43, 6, 38, 38, NULL, 'Divine Mission and Delivery', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in human affairs. Both passages emphasize the act of coming down to fulfill a mission: God to deliver His people from Egypt and Jesus to accomplish the will of the Father.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 23, 63, 8, 9, 'affliction of my people which is in Egypt', 'Affliction and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of affliction and His role in delivering His people. Acts 7:34 speaks of God''s response to the groaning of His people, while Isaiah 63:8-9 highlights His presence and salvation in their affliction.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 28, 12, 13, 13, 'I have seen the affliction of my people', 'Deliverance through Prophetic Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance, as both passages refer to God''s action in rescuing His people from Egypt. Acts 7:34 emphasizes God''s call to Moses for deliverance, while Hosea 12:13 attributes Israel''s exodus and preservation to a prophet.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 19, 118, 22, 23, 'whom they refused', 'Rejection and Divine Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages. Moses is initially refused as a ruler, paralleling the stone rejected by builders that becomes central to God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 42, 19, 14, 14, 'Who made thee a ruler', 'Rejection of Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of divinely appointed leaders. In both passages, the citizens and the people refuse to accept the authority of those chosen by God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 4, 20, 16, 16, 'the same did God send to be a ruler and a deliverer', 'Moses as Deliverer', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in sending an angel to deliver His people. Acts 7:35 refers to Moses as a ruler and deliverer, while Numbers 20:16 mentions an angel sent to bring the Israelites out of Egypt.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 19, 75, 7, 7, NULL, 'Divine Authority in Leadership', 'This connection highlights God''s role in establishing leaders. Both passages emphasize that God appoints rulers and judges according to His will.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 2, 14, 19, 19, 'by the hand of the angel', 'Divine Guidance Through Angels', 'This connection highlights the role of the angel in guiding God''s people. In Acts, Moses is sent by God through the angel, while in Exodus, the angel of God leads the Israelites.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 2, 23, 20, 23, 'the same did God send to be a ruler', 'Moses and the Angel Connection', 'This connection highlights the role of the angel as a divine messenger. Both passages emphasize God''s guidance through the angel, with Moses being appointed as a ruler and deliverer.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 9, 8, 7, 8, 'Who made thee a ruler and a judge?', 'Rejection of God''s Chosen Leaders', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of God''s appointed leaders. In both passages, the people reject Moses and Samuel, indicating a pattern of forsaking divine authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 2, 12, 41, 41, NULL, 'Exodus and Wilderness Journey', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from Egypt, as both passages describe the Israelites'' exodus. Acts 7:36 references the signs and wonders that preceded their departure, while Exodus 12:41 marks the moment they left Egypt.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 2, 14, 21, 21, 'wonders and signs in the land of Egypt', 'Moses and the Red Sea', 'This connection highlights the miraculous events associated with Moses, specifically the division of the sea. Both passages emphasize the signs and wonders performed by God through Moses during the Exodus.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 19, 78, 12, 33, 'wonders and signs in the land of Egypt', 'Miraculous Signs and Provision', 'Both passages emphasize God''s miraculous acts during the Exodus, including dividing the sea and providing sustenance in the wilderness. They highlight the theme of divine intervention and the people''s response to God''s wonders.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 4, 11, 1, 35, NULL, 'Complaints and Divine Response', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s complaints and God''s response. In Acts, the focus is on the signs and wonders during the Exodus, while Numbers details the people''s dissatisfaction with manna and God''s provision of quail, highlighting a recurring theme of discontent and divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 4, 14, 1, 45, NULL, 'Signs and Miracles in Wilderness', 'Both passages emphasize the signs and wonders shown by the Lord during the Israelites'' journey. Acts 7:36 mentions these wonders in Egypt and the wilderness, while Numbers 14:22 refers to the miracles seen by the people, highlighting their lack of faith despite witnessing God''s power.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 5, 2, 25, 37, 'wonders and signs', 'Divine Deliverance and Conquest', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in delivering Israel from their enemies. Acts 7:36 mentions the wonders and signs during the Exodus, while Deuteronomy 2:25-37 describes God''s deliverance of Sihon into Israel''s hands.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 5, 4, 33, 37, 'wonders and signs', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God demonstrating his power through signs and wonders. Acts 7:36 mentions ''wonders and signs'' performed in Egypt, while Deuteronomy 4:33-37 recounts similar acts that reveal God''s might and purpose in delivering Israel from Egypt.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 5, 18, 15, 19, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Moses and the Prophet Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of a prophet raised up by God from among the people, specifically stating he will be ''like unto me.'' This connection highlights the continuity of prophetic leadership from Moses to the anticipated future prophet.', 'prophecy', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 44, 3, 22, 23, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up unto you of your brethren, like unto me; him shall ye hear.', 'Connection of Moses and the Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize Moses'' prophecy about a prophet like him. They highlight the importance of listening to this prophet, indicating a direct link between Moses and the future figure.', 'quotation', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 43, 18, 37, 37, 'him shall ye hear', 'Connection of Prophetic Voice', 'This connection highlights the theme of prophetic authority. In Acts, Moses speaks of a prophet to be heard, while in John, Jesus emphasizes that those who are of the truth hear his voice.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 40, 17, 3, 5, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Moses and the Prophet Connection', 'This connection highlights the reference to Moses as a prophet in Acts 7:37, which parallels the appearance of Moses in Matthew 17:3-5. Both passages emphasize the importance of listening to God''s chosen messenger, as seen in the command to ''hear ye him.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 44, 7, 38, 38, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Connection Between Moses and Prophecy', 'This connection highlights Moses as a prophet and his role in delivering God''s message. Both passages emphasize the significance of Moses in the wilderness and the prophetic expectation of a future leader.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 41, 9, 7, 7, 'him shall ye hear', 'Prophetic Voice Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of prophetic authority. In Acts, Moses speaks of a prophet to be heard, while in Mark, God commands to ''hear him,'' referring to Jesus, thus linking their roles as prophets.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 42, 9, 30, 31, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Moses and Prophetic Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the role of Moses as a prophet, as indicated in Acts 7:37, and the appearance of Moses in Luke 9:30-31, where he speaks of Jesus'' impending death. Both passages emphasize the prophetic significance of Moses in relation to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 45, 3, 2, 2, 'lively oracles to give unto us', 'Connection of Oracles in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the significance of the ''oracles'' given to the Israelites. Both passages emphasize the role of these divine communications in their respective contexts.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 58, 5, 12, 12, 'oracles to give unto us', 'Connection of Oracles of God', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''oracles'' in both passages. Acts 7:38 refers to the ''lively oracles'' received in the wilderness, while Hebrews 5:12 discusses the ''oracles of God'' as foundational teachings.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 5, 33, 4, 4, 'received the lively oracles to give unto us', 'Moses and the Law Connection', 'This connection highlights Moses'' role in delivering the law to the Israelites. Both passages emphasize the importance of the law received by Moses for the congregation of Jacob.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 43, 1, 17, 17, 'lively oracles to give unto us', 'Law and Grace Connection', 'This connection highlights the transition from the law given by Moses to the grace and truth brought by Jesus Christ. Acts 7:38 refers to the ''lively oracles'' received, which can be seen as the law, while John 1:17 contrasts this with the grace and truth that Jesus embodies.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 44, 7, 53, 53, 'received the lively oracles', 'Connection of Law and Angels', 'Both passages emphasize the role of angels in delivering the law. The first mentions ''the lively oracles'' received, while the second states the law was received ''by the disposition of angels.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 60, 4, 11, 11, 'lively oracles to give unto us', 'Connection of Oracles in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''oracles'' as divine communication. Both passages emphasize the importance of speaking and ministering as representatives of God''s words.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 5, 5, 27, 31, 'received the lively oracles', 'Connection of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Moses as a mediator between God and the people, highlighting the importance of receiving divine commandments. Acts 7:38 refers to Moses receiving ''lively oracles,'' while Deuteronomy 5:27-31 discusses the people''s desire to hear God''s words through Moses.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 4, 14, 3, 4, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rejection of God''s Guidance', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to return to Egypt, reflecting disobedience and lack of faith in God''s plan. The Israelites in Acts 7:39 are described as turning back to Egypt in their hearts, paralleling the lament in Numbers 14:3-4 about returning to Egypt due to fear and doubt.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 4, 11, 5, 5, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rejection of Egypt''s Influence', 'This connection highlights the Israelites'' longing for Egypt after rejecting Moses. Both passages emphasize a desire to return to the comforts of Egypt, illustrating their disobedience and nostalgia for former provisions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 16, 9, 16, 17, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rebellion and Return to Bondage', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rebellion against God and a desire to return to Egypt or bondage. They highlight the refusal to obey God''s commandments and the hardening of hearts, illustrating a pattern of disobedience among the people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 2, 16, 3, 3, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Israel''s Rebellion and Longing for Egypt', 'This connection highlights the Israelites'' disobedience and desire to return to Egypt. Both passages emphasize a longing for the comforts of Egypt despite the hardships faced in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 26, 20, 6, 14, 'would not obey', 'Rebellion Against God', 'Both passages emphasize the rebellion of the Israelites against God after being delivered from Egypt. Acts 7:39 highlights their refusal to obey, while Ezekiel 20:6-14 details their continued idolatry and disobedience. This connection highlights a recurring theme of rejection of divine guidance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 44, 7, 51, 52, 'would not obey', 'Resistance to God''s Message', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resistance to God''s chosen leaders. In Acts 7:39, the fathers rejected Moses, paralleling the accusation in Acts 7:51-52 that the current generation resists the Holy Ghost like their ancestors did.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 2, 14, 11, 12, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rejection of Leadership and Egypt', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to return to Egypt, highlighting the Israelites'' rejection of Moses'' leadership. In Acts, the phrase ''turned back again into Egypt'' reflects their longing for the past, similar to the complaints in Exodus about preferring servitude in Egypt over facing hardship in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 40, 2, 32, 1, 1, 'for as for this Moses, which brought us out of the land of Egypt, we wot not what is become of him.', 'Connection of Idolatry and Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s demand for gods in the absence of Moses. This connection highlights their impatience and desire for visible leadership when Moses is delayed.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 40, 2, 32, 23, 23, 'as for this Moses, which brought us out of the land of Egypt', 'Connection of Idolatry and Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s demand for gods in the absence of Moses, highlighting their impatience and desire for leadership. The repetition of the phrase ''as for this Moses'' underscores their confusion regarding his fate.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 19, 106, 19, 21, 'made a calf in those days', 'Idolatry and Forgetting God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of making a calf and worshipping it, highlighting the theme of idolatry. They also reflect on the people''s forgetfulness of God, who had performed great deeds for them.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 16, 9, 18, 18, 'made a calf', 'Idolatry and the Golden Calf', 'Both passages emphasize the creation of a calf and the worship associated with it. They highlight the Israelites'' rejection of God through idolatry, showcasing their disobedience and provocations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 28, 9, 1, 1, 'rejoiced in the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and False Joy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of idolatry leading to false joy. Acts 7:41 describes the Israelites rejoicing in their idol, while Hosea 9:1 warns Israel against rejoicing due to their unfaithfulness to God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 28, 9, 10, 10, 'rejoiced in the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Abomination Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of idolatry, with Acts mentioning the ''calf'' and Hosea referencing ''Baalâ€“peor'' as examples of Israel''s turning away from God. This connection highlights the consequences of their actions, described as ''abominations'' in Hosea.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 35, 2, 18, 20, 'the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Its Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of idol worship, highlighting the contrast between man-made idols and the living God. Acts 7:41 describes the creation of an idol, while Habakkuk 2:18-20 questions the value of such graven images.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 66, 9, 20, 20, 'works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Works of Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worshiping idols made by human hands. Acts 7:41 describes the Israelites rejoicing in the works of their own hands, while Revelation 9:20 warns against the works of their hands leading to idol worship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 2, 32, 2, 8, 'rejoiced in the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Sacrifice Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of making a calf and offering sacrifices to it. Acts 7:41 references the people''s rejoicing in their own works, paralleling Exodus 32:2-8 where they proclaim the calf as their god and celebrate with offerings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 30, 5, 25, 26, 'forty years in the wilderness', 'Wilderness Sacrifices and Idolatry', 'Both passages emphasize the Israelites'' sacrifices in the wilderness and their idolatry. Acts 7:42 references the forty years of offerings, paralleling Amos 5:25-26''s mention of sacrifices while also condemning the worship of Moloch and Chiun.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 26, 20, 39, 39, 'O ye house of Israel', 'Idolatry and Divine Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Israel''s idolatry and God''s response. Both passages emphasize God''s rejection of Israel''s worship due to their devotion to idols.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 24, 19, 13, 13, 'worship the host of heaven', 'Worship of the Host of Heaven', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry and the worship of celestial beings. Both passages address the act of offering sacrifices and incense to the host of heaven, indicating a rejection of true worship.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 19, 81, 11, 12, 'gave them up', 'Divine Abandonment Theme', 'Both passages emphasize God''s response to Israel''s disobedience. Acts 7:42 mentions God giving them up, paralleling Psalms 81:11-12, where God gives them up to their own desires.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 5, 4, 19, 19, 'worship the host of heaven', 'Worship of Heavenly Hosts', 'This connection highlights the theme of worshiping the host of heaven in both passages. Acts 7:42 refers to God giving up the Israelites to worship celestial bodies, while Deuteronomy 4:19 warns against this very act of worship.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 18, 31, 26, 28, 'worship the host of heaven', 'Worship of Heavenly Bodies', 'This connection highlights the theme of worshiping celestial bodies. Both passages address the consequences of turning away from God to worship the sun and moon, emphasizing the iniquity of such actions.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 23, 63, 10, 10, 'gave them up to worship', 'Rebellion and Divine Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of Israel''s rebellion against God and His subsequent response. Both passages illustrate how Israel''s actions led to divine abandonment and conflict.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 43, 30, 5, 26, 27, 'tabernacle of Moloch', 'Connection of Moloch and Captivity', 'Both passages emphasize the worship of Moloch and the consequences of idolatry, specifically mentioning captivity as a result. The phrases regarding the tabernacle of Moloch and the imagery of captivity beyond Babylon or Damascus create a direct thematic link.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 43, 2, 20, 4, 5, 'the tabernacle of Moloch', 'Idolatry and Divine Jealousy', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry, as both passages address the worship of false gods and the consequences of such actions. Acts 7:43 mentions the worship of Moloch and Remphan, while Exodus 20:4-5 explicitly forbids the making of graven images and warns of God''s jealousy.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 43, 5, 5, 8, 9, 'the tabernacle of Moloch', 'Connection of Idolatry and Worship', 'Both passages emphasize the prohibition of making graven images and the worship of false gods. Acts 7:43 references the worship of Moloch and Remphan, which aligns with Deuteronomy 5:8-9''s command against serving idols.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 43, 3, 20, 2, 5, 'tabernacle of Moloch', 'Connection of Moloch Worship', 'Both passages emphasize the worship of Moloch and the severe consequences for such actions. Acts 7:43 references the taking up of the tabernacle of Moloch, while Leviticus 20:2-5 outlines the punishment for giving seed to Molech.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 43, 5, 4, 16, 18, 'figures which ye made to worship them', 'Idolatry and Graven Images', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry, as both passages warn against the creation and worship of images. Acts 7:43 mentions figures made for worship, paralleling Deuteronomy 4:16-18''s prohibition against making graven images.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 43, 12, 17, 16, 18, 'worship them', 'Worship of False Gods', 'Both passages emphasize the worship of false gods, specifically mentioning practices that provoke the Lord''s anger. Acts 7:43 refers to the worship of Moloch and Remphan, while 2 Kings 17:16-18 describes the worship of molten images and Baal, highlighting a common theme of idolatry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 43, 12, 18, 11, 11, 'carry you away beyond Babylon', 'Exile and Idolatry Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of exile resulting from idolatry. Both passages reference the consequences of turning away from God, leading to the Israelites'' removal from their land.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 44, 2, 25, 40, 40, 'according to the fashion that he had seen', 'Connection of Divine Instruction', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of following God''s specific instructions for the tabernacle. Acts 7:44 refers to Moses making it ''according to the fashion'' shown to him, paralleling Exodus 25:40''s directive to make it ''after their pattern.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 44, 2, 38, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Tabernacle References', 'Both passages emphasize the tabernacle of testimony, highlighting its significance in the wilderness and its construction according to divine command. This connection illustrates the continuity of God''s instructions to Moses regarding the tabernacle.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 44, 58, 8, 5, 5, 'according to the fashion that he had seen', 'Connection of Tabernacle Instructions', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of making the tabernacle according to a divine pattern. Acts 7:44 mentions Moses receiving instructions, while Hebrews 8:5 highlights the necessity of adhering to the pattern shown to him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 44, 4, 1, 50, 53, 'tabernacle of witness', 'Connection of the Tabernacle''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the tabernacle in the wilderness. Acts 7:44 refers to the tabernacle of witness, while Numbers 1:50-53 details the Levites'' responsibilities regarding the tabernacle of testimony.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
